<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT608 Modern Political Thought and Ideologies</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The primary object of Political Thought is to introduce the undergraduate students in the Department of International Relations to
      theory in political science. The focus of attention is the emergence and development of democratic theory in political science.
      Modern Political Thought and Ideologies is concerned with the fundamental questions of public life. It addresses such issues as
      the nature of political authority, the relationship of the state to the individual, and the obligations and responsibilities
      that citizens owe to one another. Over the last several decades the field of political theory has undergone a remarkable revival,
      with theorists bringing insights from classic texts to bear on present day issues. This course offers an introduction to the field
      by examining a few basic concepts - "authority", "liberty", and "justice" - and discussing some of the ways in which these concepts
      have been employed in discussions of current political issues. While some of the readings draw upon "classics" in the field - e.g.,
      Plato, Aristotle, Thomas Hobbes, John Locke, David Hume, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, and John Stuart Mill - we will also look at
      writings by present-day moral philosophers, political theorists, and social commentators and will read a number of recent Supreme
      Court decisions to see what light they cast on different ways of thinking about such issues as free speech, privacy rights, and affirmative action.
    </div>
